[{"_id":"b080602b-3370-3cf9-ac9d-ac35e0db6b02","authorName":"David","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","message":"If I used twitter I would have asked for Task. I'm looking forward to this series -- David","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"","date":"2014-04-25T20:04:31Z","timestamp":1398456271,"authorUserId":""},{"_id":"ca799327-188a-3828-b722-904d858bb3ae","authorName":"Alvin","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","message":"Awesome! Keep it coming! I'm still working in .Net 4.0 so this info will be of great interest.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"","date":"2014-04-25T05:22:12Z","timestamp":1398403332,"authorUserId":""},{"_id":"08b4f713-f71d-3df7-86d9-1479a12466ba","authorName":"sunseraphic","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"601c9639010c7c00954bc64db90d67cd","message":"Rather than a Promise, I think Task is more like a Future.  \r\nIf you want found a equivalent of Promise in C#, you should consider TaskCompletionSource.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"","date":"2014-05-29T05:41:00Z","timestamp":1401342060,"authorUserId":"disqus:sunseraphic"},{"_id":"140f6d2c-4b9d-34d1-979b-85d06a37fabc","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"ad2250182ff26a84dda974e50cd94382","message":"You are correct: the Task type itself is a Future, and TaskCompletionSource is a Promise.\r\n\r\nThe terminology I'm using (\"Delegate Task\" vs \"Promise Task\") refers to the *source* of the task. So I'm using the term \"Promise Task\" as meaning \"Task that comes from a Promise\", i.e., a Task created from a TaskCompletionSource (or one of its shorthands such as async).\r\n\r\nBut part of my blog post does refer to the tasks themselves as promises; I'll correct that.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"08b4f713-f71d-3df7-86d9-1479a12466ba","date":"2014-05-30T13:03:12Z","timestamp":1401454992,"authorUserId":"disqus:stephen_cleary"},{"_id":"1b30e4bf-fca2-307d-b3c9-2940a9d3b783","authorName":"Tyler Fang","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"cc7d10b4a2808363c976d60bfd2fff60","message":"I have to say this is one of the best organized blog/tutorial I could find to date.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"","date":"2016-07-26T17:27:58Z","timestamp":1469554078,"authorUserId":"disqus:tylerfang"},{"_id":"0b84a781-f345-31dc-9052-6c207eed3100","authorName":"Kevin Marois","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"c2aa8431b25b6b25c130318fd8267aff","message":"No worries. I've been working on an app that works like DropBox, and I'm using SignalR to send real-time file upload notifications to all connected clients.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that there's not a lot of info out there on SignalR. I did buy this book: [https://www.amazon.com/Sign...](https://www.amazon.com/SignalR-Programming-Microsoft-Developer-Reference/dp/0735683883/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1479409224&sr=1-2&keywords=SignalR \"https://www.amazon.com/SignalR-Programming-Microsoft-Developer-Reference/dp/0735683883/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1479409224&sr=1-2&keywords=SignalR\")\r\n\r\n... but assumes you're a Java dev, which I'm not. The MS website for SignalR is OK, and there are some mediocre samples. Just curious if you knew of any other resources.  \r\nBTW, great blog. Keep it up.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"e510e896-62c4-3a6c-b61f-e94cf15f4e4b","date":"2016-11-17T19:02:27Z","timestamp":1479409347,"authorUserId":"disqus:kevin_marois"},{"_id":"40f18bb3-f515-3f78-bc89-a29a7b98dc22","authorName":"Kevin Marois","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"c2aa8431b25b6b25c130318fd8267aff","message":"Stephen, you mentioned SignalR here. Have you done any articles on it? I'm working with SignalR and would like more resources. Thanks","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"","date":"2016-11-17T16:33:30Z","timestamp":1479400410,"authorUserId":"disqus:kevin_marois"},{"_id":"e510e896-62c4-3a6c-b61f-e94cf15f4e4b","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"ad2250182ff26a84dda974e50cd94382","message":"No, sorry. I am still planning to write that series, but writing is very slow for me, and it'll actually be more of a \"Here's how much SignalR does for you, so stop thinking TCP/IP is easy\" series of articles, not really a SignalR tutorial.","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"40f18bb3-f515-3f78-bc89-a29a7b98dc22","date":"2016-11-17T18:55:49Z","timestamp":1479408949,"authorUserId":"disqus:stephen_cleary"},{"_id":"b350d1d9-9da1-357d-a956-0718f88a9787","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"ad2250182ff26a84dda974e50cd94382","message":"Sorry for the delayed reply - apparently Disqus has been going a bit crazy marking all sorts of stuff as spam on my blog, and I just noticed today.\r\n\r\nAnyway, I don't know of good documentation for SignalR. They're working on Core support, and some of the APIs have changed, so I'd start just using the new stuff if possible: [https://github.com/aspnet/S...](https://github.com/aspnet/SignalR \"https://github.com/aspnet/SignalR\")","postId":"2014_04_a-tour-of-task-part-0-overview-764a5b18-7251-3d67-a42d-7ef196c838ee","replyTo":"0b84a781-f345-31dc-9052-6c207eed3100","date":"2017-10-04T16:08:03Z","timestamp":1507133283,"authorUserId":"disqus:stephen_cleary"}]